 definitions or essences, but on the ineluctable repetitions that constitute language as such, and that guarantee the expansiveness—through etymological coincidences of meaning, through historical contagions, through translinguistic sharings of particular experiences—of a certain index of universality. This edition includes a new introduction by the author and three entirely new chapters, as well as updated images and corrections to the original translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aQuotation in literature. 4aEducation : Literacy Studies. 4aLanguage Arts : Semiotics. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Language. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aEgginton, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRayAlexander, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438450322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438450322/original  a978-3-11-149015-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles